Theater Dance Group Presents
Outstandingly Unified Performance

By RONNIE FULTON

Last Friday and Saturday night
ili Roberts Theater, the' Grinnell
community was treated to an
evening ot excellent dance and
some very good choreography by
the Theater Dance Group, for
inerly known as Orchesis. The
varied program provided an ex-
citingshow for theaudience,

The Theater Dance Group. as
compared with last year‘s group,
has learned to work and dance
as a group. A college dance group
with only a few good dancers
could not have prowded such a
diversified program, The pres
ence of so many new males in
-the performance, noted with
great pleasure, is one factor re-
sponsible for a more cohesive
group,

The first half of the program
was choreographed primarily by
students, “Organic,“ choreo-
graphed by Giti Zarnegar, was
one of the best attempts. The out
standing piece of student
choreography was ”Street Peo-
pie,” danced to music by Cop-
land. and choreographed by Dick
Hartz, Harlz obviously has potenr
tial as a choreographer, In this
number he managed to create
humorous character sketches of
street vendors and young cou-

ples. He knows how to shift the
audience‘s attention from cou-

pla, to individuals, to the group.
The simplicity of the dramatic
elements in this piece made the
story easily understood. Another
student piece, “Character Stud-
ies From Theater,“ would have
profited from a less complicated
plot.

l-lartz’ other example of
choreography was his solo,
“David at Gilboa.” This short,
simple number succeeded in
creating a mood of nobility. Hartz
began the piece with very simple
movements which he later de-
veloped The shadow of his figure
playing on the back wall added
an excellent touch.

Ofall the pieces choreographed
by Mrs. Voertman, “Gnossiena
nes," “Full Circle,” and “The
Last Flower” were most success-
ful “The Last Flower” contained
more acting than dance; how
ever, the audience seemed to
enjoy the humor of the group's
portrayal of such things as rab-
bits and subways. In “Full Cir-
cle,” the story of the jealousies
of two women and a man, Mrs.
Voertman displayed her ability
to combine the serious and the
comic. Nina Seidenman was an

<t‘ser's political

excellent choice for the female
rolc opposite Mrs. Voertman. The
contrast in the shapes of their
bodies and their facial features
complemented the theme of the
struggle between the two women.
“Gnussiennes,” danced by Jenny
Butcher, Elly Dayton, and Sue
Seeder, was one of the most
beautiful numbers in the
program, In this piece Mrs.
Voertmari created a simplicity of
movement, tastefully begun and
resolved. The gracefulness of the
dance was reminiscent of the
style of Martha Graham.

The audience thoroughly en-
joyed the performance. This re-
viewer hopes to See the Theater
Dance Group retain its cohesive
character, and to see Dick Hartz
continue with his ambitious
choreography. Mrs Voertman is
to be commended for her choreo-
graphic ability and her ability to
teach dancers to change thought
into the movement of one body.

