with the fingerboard reflects his
classical training. The most imr
pressive quality about his unique
style is the apparent. ray-Alps:
ease with which he‘llips off delir
cate trills, harpsichordial
moi-dents and incredible intricate
runs. Cox's voice, big and
resonant to begin with, filled up
the room even more as time went
on.

Cox’s popularity at Grinnell may
also be attributed to his unpre-
tentious manner, warm person~
ality, and quiet humor. He is
perTéctly at home in front ot an
audience and obviously enjoys
himself, with the result that the
audience can do none other than
enjoy him.

